<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers · 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Read a Settlement Statement When Selling Your Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Your solicitor will send you a settlement statement before your property settles. Here is what every line item means and what to check before you sign off.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most Brisbane vendors selling their first property are surprised by the settlement statement. Not because it is complicated, but because the final net proceeds figure is almost always different from the number they calculated in their head. Agent commission, solicitor fees, rate adjustments, and mortgage discharge costs all appear on the statement, often for the first time as actual figures rather than estimates. Understanding what each line item means before the statement arrives makes the process significantly less stressful.</p>

      <p>The settlement statement is a formal financial reconciliation prepared by your solicitor, typically delivered two to three business days before the scheduled settlement date. It summarises every financial transaction connected to the sale and shows the net amount that will be transferred to you after all deductions and adjustments are applied. It is not the contract; it is the financial accounting of what the contract commits to in dollar terms.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The sale price and deposit</h2>
      <p>The statement starts with the agreed purchase price from your contract of sale. The deposit paid by the buyer at exchange is usually held in trust by your agent or solicitor during the campaign and is credited against the purchase price at settlement. On the statement, you will typically see the full sale price as a credit, with the deposit shown as already received or held in trust. The balance owing from the buyer is the purchase price minus the deposit they have already paid.</p>

      <p>If the buyer paid a deposit in stages (an initial holding deposit followed by a full 10% deposit), both payments should appear. Confirm that the deposit figures on the statement match what was actually paid and receipted during the campaign. Discrepancies here are rare but worth checking.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Agent commission and marketing costs</h2>
      <p>Your agent's commission is shown as a deduction from the sale price. In Queensland, commissions are negotiated rather than regulated, but a typical range for inner-Brisbane residential property is between 2% and 2.75% of the sale price plus GST. The exact figure will match what was agreed in your Form 6 appointment with the agent. If there is a performance-based or tiered commission structure in the Form 6, the statement will reflect whichever tier applied based on the final sale price.</p>

      <p>Out-of-pocket marketing costs, if they were agreed to be paid at settlement rather than upfront, will also appear as a deduction. These typically include the online listing fee (realestate.com.au and Domain), photography and video production, and any print or signage costs. If you paid marketing costs upfront during the campaign, they should not appear again on the settlement statement. Confirm this with your agent before settlement if you are unsure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mortgage discharge and payout figure</h2>
      <p>If you have a mortgage on the property, your bank or lender must be paid out from the settlement proceeds before you receive anything. Your solicitor will have contacted your lender to obtain a payout figure, which is the total amount required to discharge the mortgage as at the settlement date. This figure includes the principal balance, accrued interest to the settlement date, and the lender's discharge fee (typically $150 to $350 depending on the lender).</p>

      <p>The payout figure is date-specific. If settlement is delayed by even a few days, the interest component increases slightly and your solicitor will need to obtain an updated figure. Keep this in mind if settlement is extended or if you are monitoring the net proceeds closely. The discharge payout is shown as a deduction from the sale price on the settlement statement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Council and water rate adjustments</h2>
      <p>Property rates are levied in advance in Queensland. Council rates are typically billed quarterly, and water rates are billed twice yearly. Settlement almost never falls exactly at the end of a billing period, which means the rates bill for the current period has to be split between vendor and buyer in proportion to how many days each party occupies the property during that billing cycle. This split is called an adjustment.</p>

      <p>If you have already paid the full rates bill for a period that extends past settlement, the buyer owes you a refund for the days after settlement. This appears as a credit to you on the statement. If the bill has not yet been paid and covers days before settlement, you owe the buyer the days up to settlement, which appears as a deduction. The adjustments are usually small (a few hundred dollars either way) but they can sometimes catch vendors off-guard if they have not paid a rates notice recently.</p>

      <p>Body corporate levies work the same way if you are selling a unit or townhouse. The current levy period is adjusted to the settlement date, and the statement will show either a credit or a deduction depending on whether you have already paid ahead.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Solicitor fees</h2>
      <p>Your own solicitor's conveyancing fees appear as a deduction on the statement. These typically cover the preparation of the contract (if your solicitor drafted it), title searches, preparation of transfer documentation, liasing with your lender for the discharge, and attendance at settlement. Legal fees for a straightforward Queensland residential sale typically range from $1,200 to $2,500 plus disbursements, though they vary significantly by firm and complexity.</p>

      <p>Disbursements are the out-of-pocket costs your solicitor incurs on your behalf: title search fees, bank cheque fees, and similar. These are itemised separately from the professional fee and are generally modest in total. If your solicitor's fees on the statement differ significantly from the estimate they gave you when you engaged them, ask for a breakdown before settlement rather than after.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to check before signing off</h2>
      <p>When the settlement statement arrives, work through the following checks. Confirm the sale price matches the contract. Confirm the deposit figure matches what was paid. Verify the agent commission matches the agreed percentage in your Form 6. Check that marketing costs are not double-counted if you paid them upfront. Confirm the mortgage payout figure is current and your lender has confirmed they will attend settlement to release the title. Check both rate adjustment calculations against your actual rates notices to verify the billing period dates are correct.</p>

      <p>The most common discrepancies sellers find are small errors in rate adjustment dates (using the wrong billing cycle start date), marketing costs that were paid upfront still appearing as a deduction, and lender discharge fees that differ from the standard fee schedule. None of these are fraud; they are usually errors that are straightforward to correct before settlement. Your solicitor should be able to resolve any discrepancy within a day or two if you raise it promptly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the net proceeds are transferred to you</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, settlement has historically been conducted in person at the Land Titles Office or at the offices of the buyer's solicitor. The PEXA electronic conveyancing platform is now used for most settlements in Queensland, which means settlement happens electronically and proceeds are transferred automatically into your nominated bank account on the day of settlement, usually by mid-afternoon. Your solicitor will confirm the settlement time the day before.</p>

      <p>If settlement is conducted via PEXA, the funds are typically available the same day. If settlement occurs via paper for any reason, bank processing times may add one business day before the funds clear. Your solicitor will advise on the timing based on how settlement is being conducted for your transaction. It is worth confirming your bank account details with your solicitor at least one week before settlement to avoid any last-minute issues with incorrect account numbers.</p>

